ment with soul. While each work offers fascinating and challenging insights, there has never been as extensive a commentary covering them together. A reason is that the works have often been viewed as incidental and even inconsistent. The De motu animalium has not typically been included, when viewed as an isolated work on animal locomotion. This commentary argues that the treatises, considered together and with the De motu among them, display a tight sequence manifesting an artful, yet easily overlooked, design. We reveal many techniques of Aristotle’s writing that have received little consideration previously. Our commentary contributes to a unified and comprehensive account of Aristotle’s overall project regarding the soul and its connections with the body.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPsychology. 4aErinnerung. 4aLebensführung. 4aSchlaf und Traum. 4aSinneswahrnehmung. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  alife maintenance.  amemory.  asense perception.  asleep and dreams.1 aPolansky, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cEPUBz97831112440440 cprintz978311123574540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311124383240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111243832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111243832/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles